## File Conventions
- SQL files: snake_case with descriptive names (e.g., in_month_conversion.sql)
- Planning docs: UPPER_SNAKE_CASE.md (e.g., QUICKSTART.md)
- Configuration: lowercase with dashes (e.g., .gitlab-ci.yml)
- All SQL files go in bigquery/ directory
- All planning docs go in root

## BigQuery SQL Style Guide
- Always use CREATE OR REPLACE VIEW for idempotent deployment
- Fully-qualified table names: \`gen-lang-client-0844868008.dataset.table\`
- Use CTEs (WITH clauses) for readable, modular query logic
- One CTE per logical transformation step
- Comment every CTE with its purpose and data flow
- Use ROW_NUMBER() OVER (PARTITION BY ... ORDER BY ...) for deduplication
- Use COALESCE() for null handling in joins and aggregations
- Use SAFE_DIVIDE() to prevent divide-by-zero errors
- Use SAFE.PARSE_TIMESTAMP() for flexible timestamp parsing
- Lowercase all identifiers (table names, column names, aliases)
- Uppercase SQL keywords (SELECT, FROM, WHERE, JOIN, etc.)
- Use meaningful column aliases with units (e.g., expected_arr, won_count, pct_lost)

## BigQuery Naming Conventions
- Views: snake_case (e.g., corp_penetration_view, in_month_conversion)
- Columns: snake_case with suffix indicating type (_count, _arr, _pct, _rate)
- CTEs: descriptive snake_case (e.g., deal_base, som_snapshot, combined_metrics)
- Temporal columns: _start, _end, _at suffixes (e.g., month_start, snapshot_ts)
- Boolean columns: was_, is_, has_ prefix (e.g., was_open_start_of_month, is_expected)

## Section Comment Pattern
Every SQL file should use this comment structure:
-- ============================================================
-- SECTION N: Title
-- ============================================================
-- Description of what this section does

## Dataset Reference
- Project ID: gen-lang-client-0844868008
- Analytics dataset: revops_analytics
